:"1256–1326","1254–1298":"1254–1298","1275–1349":"1275–1349","1229–1284":"1229–1284","1234–1284":"1234–1284","1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1284":"1284","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1326":"1326","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1234":"1234","1256":"1256","1298":"1298","1254":"1254","Aft 1284":"after 1284","about 1256":"about 1256","about 1284":"about 1284","about 1251":"about 1251","1317":"1317","1229":"1229","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Abington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Abington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thornton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":3,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":34,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":59,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hung